Beilschmiedia osacola

is vegetatively recognized because it is a large tree, the bark is reddish, and peeling in large plates (
Figure 3A–D
), by its alternate leaves, not densely grouped at the apex of the twigs, the lower leaf surface glabrous and not glaucous (
Figure 3G
), with tertiary veins reticulate (
Figure 3H
), and relatively long and thin petioles. The flowers stand out by their tiny size (
Figures 2D–G
, 
4B
), by the perianth with receptacle on outer surface pubescent, and tepals slightly unequal; the androecium is composed of six fertile stamens (whorls I and II), while the whorls III and IV are staminodial. The stamens of whorl III are columnar, pubescent, with two large glands attached near the base; the ovary is pubescent (
Figure 2E, F
). The new species shares with 

B. costaricensis

(Mez & Pittier in 
Mez 1903: 228
) C.K. 
Allen (1945: 415)
the areolate tertiary venation with free-ending veinlets, but it differs from that species in its uniformly pubescent ovary, the tepals clearly shorter than the hypanthium and the multiflowered and laxly branched inflorescences.
